summary.seg: The manuscript is closely related to Cambridge, Christ's College, MS Rouse 358; both are anthologies of Greek literary texts copied by Carolus Stephanus. MS Rouse 359 contains works by Sophocles, Pindar, Hesiod and Aeschylus. The texts of the Greek poets are accompanied by numerous extracts from various encyclopaedias and commentaries from the 16th century; for example, the Greek hypotheses to Sophocles' tragedies are accompanied by Latin translations by the German humanist Thomas Naogeorgus (ca. 1511-1563), published in 1558. The periocha (very short summaries of the tragedies, on sect. 1, p. [viii]) and the notes copied in the margins of the tragedies are also taken from this same translation.
Although it does not seem to have been intended to be divided into volumes, the manuscript is conceived in four sections, each with independent pagination.

support.material: Western paper, in folio. Watermark: Greek cross in a circle on three mounts with four circles ( 35 35 ) middle of the folio, on a chainlines comparable to Piccard, 16-10-2896 . The majority of those examples are dated from 1560s.

supportDesc.foliation: sect. 1: pp. [i-xvi] + 1-171 + 172[a-c] + 173-229 + 230[a-c] + 231-427 + [428-434]; sect. 2: pp. [i-viii] + 1-271 + [272-278]; sect. 3: pp. [i-vii] + 1 + 2[a], 2[b] - 35[a], 35[b] + 36-39 + [40-42]; sect. 4: pp. [i-x] + 1-55 + [56-62]. Original pagination in ink in Arabic numerals on external upper corner. It starts from the first page of the text of each tome. In sect. 2 the pages are numbered by openings.

collation.p:
The manuscript consists of 41 quires (sect 1 quires 1-22; sect. 2 quires 22-34; sect. 3 quires 34-38; sect. 4 quires 38-41):
Quire 14+2 sect. 1, pp. [i-xii]
Quire 210 sect. 1, pp. [xiii]-16
Quire 38 sect. 1, pp. 17-32
Quires 4-910 sect. 1, pp. 33-152
Quire 1010+1 sect. 1, pp. 153-172
Quire 1112 sect. 1, pp. 173-196
Quires 12-1310 sect. 1, pp. 197-236
Quire 1410+1 sect. 1, pp. 237-256
Quires 15-2112 sect. 1, pp. 257-424
Quire 2210-1 sect. 1, p. 425 - sect. 2, p. [viii]
Quire 238 sect. 2, pp. 1-16
Quires 24-3412 sect. 2, p. 17 - sect. 3, p. [ii]
Quire 353 sect. 3, pp. [iii-viii]
Quire 3620-1 sect. 3, pp. 1-20[a]
Quire 3722-4 sect. 3, pp. 20[b]-[40]
Quire 386-1 sect. 3, p. [41] - sect. 4, p. [viii]
Quires 39-4012 sect. 4, pp. [ix]-46
Quire 418 sect. 4, pp. 46-[62]
collation.catchwords: Original horizontal catchwords on every page with text, on right-hand corner.
collation.signatures: Original quire signatures present in sections 1 and 2, in brown ink in Latin letters, on the first folio of each quire, recto, bottom left. It restarts at the beginning of section 2. Section 1: A (p. [v]) - I, K-T, V-X. Section 2: A (p. 1) - I, K-L.

handNote.p: The manuscript is entirely written by Stephanus, Carolus Carolus Stephanus in mixed minuscule, characterized by marked contrast between thick and thin strokes, the cursive style and the large size of capital letters.

decoDesc.decoNote: Numerous stencilled ornaments placed to fill in empty spaces at the end of books or to separate hypotheses from books, e.g.: sect. 1, pp. 51, 112, 113, 114, 171, 172[c].
Oval printed frames have been glued on the pages that serve as frontispieces of the sections: sect. 1, p. [v], sect. 2, p. [iii], sect. 3, p. [iii],

additions.p: A circular book-plate pasted on sect. 1, pp. [v] and [x] containing the three coats of arms of the city Nuremberg and that of the Behaim von Schwarzburg family of Nuremberg connected by loops; lettered above Bib: Nor: (Bibliotheca Norica) (cf. F. Warnecke, Die deutschen Bücherzeichen (ex-libris), Berlin 1890, no. 1473).
Leaf tab markers in parchment pasted on sect. 1, p. [vii], sect. 2, p. [i], sect. 4, p. [i].

binding.p: Light brown parchment over paste-laminate boards. The thongs are laced through the parchment joint and pasted onto the inner side of the boards. There are four slits through each board that were for fastenings. Some slits and punched holes are present on the cover that might indicate reuse of the parchment. Lettering on the left board and the spine with titles of contents. Sprinkled red and blue on the edges.

history.origin: The manuscript was copied by Carolus Stephanus Stephanus, Carolus , between 1552 and 1592, according to the dates on section frontispieces: sect. 1, p. [v] 1589, sect. 2, p. [iii] 1589, sect. 3, p. [iii] 1552, sect. 4, p. [v] 1592. In all likelihood it was copied in Augsburg (Germany).
history.provenance: Owned by Behaim von Schwarzburg family of Nuremberg.
history.acquisition: Presented to Christ's College in 1940 by William Henry Denham Rouse (1863-1950) Rouse, W.H.D. (William Henry Denham), 1863-1950 , Fellow of the College from 1888 to 1894, Honorary Fellow from 1933 until his death, and headmaster of the Perse School in Cambridge.
